 adoptee, examines this long-term journey, with a particular focus on the race-making process and the contradictions inherent to the model minority myth.Drawing on in-depth interviews with Korean adoptee adults, online surveys, and participant observation at Korean adoptee events across the US and in Korea, Out of Place illustrates how Korean adoptees come to understand their racial positions, reconcile competing expectations of citizenship and racial and ethnic group membership, and actively work to redefine belonging both individually and collectively. In considering when and how Korean adoptees have been remade, rejected, and celebrated as exceptional citizens, Out of Place brings to the fore the features of the race-making process.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdopted childrenzKorea (South). 0aAdopted childrenzUnited States. 0aCitizenshipzUnited States. 0aImmigrantszUnited States. 0aIntercountry adoptionzKorea (South). 0aIntercountry adoptionzUnited States. 0aKorean Americans. 0aKoreanszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh  aAsian American.  aKorean adoptee.  aKorean adoption.  acitizenship.  aexceptional belonging.  afamily socialization.  afamily.  aimmigrant.  aracialized emotions.  arefusals of belonging.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075164240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479814831.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479814831423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479814831/original  a978-3-11-075164-2  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles